markdown:
Hi, my name's Ashi. Today's talk is the first in a series called
*Living Things*. This one is about language.

data.note:
Hi, my name's Ashi. Today's talk is the first in a series called
*Living Things*. This one is about language.

I'm making a language.note:
I am actually writing a programming language. This is not the big
reveal. It's not quite ready yet. But what's fascinated me about
this process is how it is in some sense completely free. You can
shape the language like anything.

And that is slightly terrifying. It's the thing most like pure math
that I've ever done: setting out into the world of concepts and
drawing shapes and lines, essentially arbitrarily.

And yet, in another sense, it's not arbitrary at all. There are some
design decisions that would be clearly wrong. And others that are—frustratingly,
usually a bit less clearly—right.

The language is taking shape, and in some sense, it's taking its own
shape.

I can tell as I design it that there's something it wants to be.

Languages Are Living Things.note:
We've all heard that languages are living things. I think we treat this
as metaphor. Languages that are spoken by people today—those we call "alive".
Languages that are no longer spoken—or are only spoken by a select
group of academics—those we describe as "dead".

For the next thirty minutes, I want you to try and take this
as literally as possible. Hopefully I'll do a bit to convince you
of this. Languages do not breathe, they do not
metabolize, but they do shape the worlds of their speakers,
they reproduce, they consume resources, they come into equilibria
with their environments—environments which, notably, include our minds
and bodies.

Language is Powerful.note:
Language is powerful. Ancient and contemporary magical systems rely
on the power of naming. The names we give to the things in our world
create that world. You've heard, I'm sure, that the hardest
problem in computer science is giving name to things. And that's
because names matter. Names are connected to meanings, linked into
this web of implications that fishes out of the depths of our minds
everything from machine schematics to childhood trauma.

Language is in The Body.note:
Language has a reputation for being airy. Disconnected from the
physical. From our bodies. "Shhhhhh," your lover might say. No
talking now. Just dance.

But this reputation, I think, conceals a vital truth: language
is a thing of the body. Our bodies are made for language. For sign,
for speech, for song. And language is a thing that grows out of
our bodies, is rooted in movement, has evolved with us, and is as
much a thing of our bodies as our thumbs, as our frontal cortex,
as our dance.

So right now...

markdown:
I want you to remember.

Remember that you have a body.

Remember your lungs, peeling open to draw in air
so the hemoglobin inside them can release CO2 and trap oxygen.

You are alive, so you are made up of living things.

I want you to remember.

Remember that you have a body.

Remember your lungs, peeling open to draw in air
so the hemoglobin inside them can release CO2 and trap oxygen.

You are alive, so you are made up of living things.

Cells.note:
Remember the cells of your body. Remember the fibers of your muscles.

Remember your heart, squeezing and squishing your blood around to drive
oxidization in your cells.

Remember that oxidization is burning, and so inside of you are thirty seven
trillion tiny fires.

Crackling.note:
Remember the crackling of depolarizing membranes in your brain, neurons
strobing with information.

You are alive, so you are a part of living things. You are a cell
within tissues shaped like cities and families and nations.

You are alive, so you hvae come from living things.
Remember your ancestors. Remember the story that has brought you here.
Remember your past.

Remember... about ten years ago.

We Were Creating.note: Ten years ago we were creating

Socially networked.note:
*socially* networked, made by us, consumed by us.
Bloggers and tweeters sharing their worlds with each other.

All of us creators, all of us consumers.

No longer would we be beholden to newspapers, to reporters. No longer would
we get our stories filtered through layers of intermediaries,
each one spinning and slanting. No, we would just get the truth.
The truth would win.

Of course, there were nay sayers. Negative nancies.
"Journalists", "researchers", asking...
okay, well, how? How, exactly? How do you know people are who they
say they are? How can you trust these faceless barely-people,
veiled by layers of cable and protocol?

And our response—my response, certainly, the one I said on the
inside—was that it's... fine... probably. Something something
web of trust. Wisdom of crowds.

Arab Spring.note: This is the time of the Arab Spring!

Obamas.note:
Barack Hussein Obama has just been elected because of us.
Global warming: definitely happening, very bad,
but we’re *going to fix it*. See, we are powerful.

A New Culture.note:
We have been weaving ourselves a new culture.

Connecting in a new way.

Without Nations and Borders.note:
Richer. More direct.
Organic. We are becoming something, all of us together
becoming something greater than any of us. It seemed,
then, that we were struck by lightning, and far from
killing us, it gave us life, and our mycelium was bearing fruit.

This is why we built everything. Remember that feeling?
The promise of the Internet, of cyberspace, this new kind
of a place without nations and borders, a place where
authoritarians fear to tread.

Punch Only Masks.note:
A place where their iron fists can punch only masks;
where their walls cannot be built because the network perceives
their censorship as damage and routes around it. Where we rely
on each other. On consensus. On the wisdom of the mob.
A place where every story can be told, true or not.

Racism.note:
A place where
your footprints can follow you forever. A place where you can
be yourself and so can anyone else; a place where everyone can
find their people and dance in 14/88 time;

New Minds.note:
a place where new minds
are growing, and they’re sprouting eyes everywhere, and their
hands are everywhere, and they are learning from us how to be
human and so far they can reliably emulate three things

Retrospect.note:
In retrospect, those journalists, those researchers,
everyone concerned, perhaps even alarmed about how we would
be able to trust anything in a world with amplification and
no accountability? They had a really solid point. Just...very solid.
Good job, Cassandra. We probably should have listened.

Yeah. But we didn’t.

And now, we’re all... completely fucked.

What happened.note:
Maybe.

It certainly feels that way sometimes.

I believe life will thrive.
I believe we will touch the stars.
I believe we will grow cities from trees,
I believe we will create space for all living things.
I believe in us.

But goodness, we don't make it easy.

I mean, Uncle Sam, always a bit of a crotchety racist,
is *really* not looking so hot these days.

And it's not just him. There's a lot of scary things happening
all over the world.

I wouldn't have believed it if you'd told me ten years ago.

May not believe it now.note:
In fact, I get a lot of my news from Twitter, so I only kindof
believe it now.

What’s the saying? Falsehood flies, truth comes limping after.
And this makes sense! We should expect this.

There are so very, very many things that can go wrong in
communication, it's a miracle we are able to communicate anything
at all.

But we do. Reliably, repeatedly, across great distances.

With a powerful new technology.

That technology is language.

You may disagree with me calling language a technology.

You may say it's not physical. But as all of us here at this programming
language conference know, technologies do not have to be physical.

It doesn't have a singular inventor, either. In fact,
some elements of language acquisition seem to be hardwired into
us.

Deaf children will create their own sign languagres.

Communities who don't already share a language will create one.

But many of our technologies do not have singular inventors. Many
of them have been discovered and re-discovered time and again,
in many different places.

There's a lot of theories on how language came to be.

markdown:
One theory, favored by Noam Chomsky, says that it arose suddenly, about
100,000 years ago, the result of a small number of mutations in a singular
individual that gave that person's brain the ability to process what Chomsky
calls "digital infinity".

This powerful capability spread like a seed crystal in the early human mind,
opening up the capacity for language and modern human cognition.

You may know it by its other name: recursion.

Embedding.note:
All human languages contain the ability to expand at their
phrases indefinitely.

Here, we can keep expanding this noun phrase by adding complementizers,
which themselves contain noun phrases, a recursive embedding that creates
the possibility of an infinitely long sentence, built through the recursive
application of a finite number of rules. Digital infinity.

In his book *The Recursive Mind*, Michael Corballis theorizes that it is this
capacity for recursion that distinguishes human thought from the cognitive
processes of other animals.

Three.note:
Corballis, in fact, identifies a magic number: three. Three layers. Three
stack frames, if you will, seems to be about the number of recursive layers
that humans can hold at once.

But that's enough.

Past present future.note:
One stack frame gives you a moment. Two gives you a delta—a direction.

But three? With three stack frames, we can hold the past, present,
and future: a temporal triumverate that's nearly universal in human
experience, represented in the tenses of nearly every language.

With three stack frames, we get direction, and meta-direction. We get
stories.

We are stories.note:
And that is the root of the self: we are stories telling ourselves.

We're all familiar with it: the little voice inside our head. It
speaks in our voice. Our inner narrative.

Turns out, it's not so inner.

Actually Saying Them.note:
Turns out you hear them because you are *actually saying them*.

Almost.

You're saying them, just... very quietly. Without any vocal
oomph to go with it.

When you speak internally, you *subvocalize*.

That is, your brain actually sends to your body the a softer
shadow of the motor impulses that would cause
you to speak the words. For sign language users, these motor
impulses go to the arms, hands, and face. For speaking people,
they go to the tongue and larynx.

Echoes.note:
Echoes of these impulses then return to the brain. You feel a
*little* like you're actually hearing speech, or seeing signs.
This sensation can then be processed by the same mechanisms we
use to process words said by anyone else.

Reading the written word is, effectively, a type-coercion operation.
We need to convert pictures of words into a stream of words-meanings.
And since we *already have* a way to convert words that we hear or
signs that we see into word-meanings, our brain just... uses that.

The Loop.note:
This process also gives longevity to the words we're holding in our
head.

The Baddley model holds that there is effectively no storage for
words that exists purely in the brain. We have a short-term
phonological store, but information held there decays very quickly,
unless it's committed to long-term memory, or refreshed.

Refreshing our word buffer is where the "Loop" part of the "Phonological
Loop" comes in. If we want to hold some piece of information in
our minds, we need to refresh our phonological store through rehearsal.

You’re familiar with rehearsal: it’s what you’re doing when you mutter
a phone number to yourself, over and over

..."8675309" "8675309"...

...Trying to keep the memory of it from decaying. You are bouncing
the pattern of the words off your body so that you can perceive them
again and refresh your memory.

So this is how our brains store words in working memory. Using
our bodies as buffers.

Reading.note:
Subvocalization is particularly noticeable in kids, because it's often
not "sub" at all. I remember watching my niece play when she was younger.
She would narrate what she was doing, constantly, to nobody in particular.

And this that's pretty normal. Early in the language-acquisition phase, you'll
often find kids narrating their inner speech out loud, or by explicitly
signing it, before developing subvocalization.
      
Same thing with reading. We mostly learn to read by reading aloud, and
traces of this fact never really go away.

Evidence.note:
In fact, one of the pieces of evidence for this comes from reading
comprehension. If you make people hold their tongues against the
roofs of their mouths while they're reading a passage, they show
poorer comprehension of the text than people who you've gotten to
do some unrelatedly annoying motor task, like tapping their fingers.

Pinning the tongue literally pins your inner tongue, muffling your
inner voice.

This is an almost bizzarely prosaic explanation for something that
seems so intimate: our inner voice.

If this is happening, surely we could detect it? And even do speech
recognition on it?

markdown:
Yes, we can.

Arnav Kapur at MIT has built a proof of concept silent computing platform,
which uses speech recognition via Electromyography—reading the electrical
impulses sent to your muscles.

Using this input, the system is able to perform speech recognition on
the words you're saying in your head. It can reply to you as well, via
bone transduction.

All this to create a silent computing platform that can be an
“intelligence augmentation device.”

It recognizes the question you're saying in your head, asks
Google about it, and answers by vibrating the bones of your jaw.

markdown:
The cerebellum is quite special.

It contains half the neurons in our nervous system.

All action commands from the brain to the body route through it

All sensations from the body to the brain, too

It has long been recognized as vitally important to our motor coordination.

Like this: **touch end of clicker**

People with cerebellar damage have difficulty performing this action smoothly.

With cerebellar damage, our movements become jerky, laggy.

Smith Predictor.html: <cite>Miall, Weir, Wolpert, and Stein — Is the cerebellum a Smith Predictor? (1993)</cite>
Smith Predictor.note:
It's theorized that the cerebellum acts as a Smith predictor.
Our brain's controller for our latency-distant bodies
able to estimate the body's current state
integrate sensory feedback to update that model
and decompose gross actions generated elsewhere in the brain
into a fine-tuned, continuously adjusted control signal

Once you've evolved it, such a thing has many uses.

Movement is a Reduce Operation.note:
Processing movement is a kind of reduce operation.

Say you're trying to spear a bison.

First, you need to know where the bison will be by the time you
throw the spear. So you take a stream of input from your senses
and decode observations. Based on the patterns of light and dark
cast on your retina, you recognize shapes and patterns and, eventually,
creatures, movement, and gestures.

Then you reduce that stream of gestures into a model for the bison:
where is it going to be at some future time `t`?

Now you know where you want the spear to be. So now, all you have
to do is run that entire process in reverse, to create a sequence
of commands for your own movements that will deliver the spear
to that point, at time `t` in the future.

Then you cue those commands, and throw the spear.

Language is Reduce.note:
Language, too, is a reduce operation.

When we're listening, we are reducing a sequence of words into a
meaning: a model describing the movement of the speaker in cognitive
space.

When we speak, we need to serialize an inner meaning into a sequence
of words.

With both language and movement, we are transforming coordinate
spaces: translating the state of our inner worlds—a point within
some space of all possible experiences—into a sequence of moves
that will move us to that point.

Whether the point is cognitive or physical doesn't really matter—the
math is the same. Language is dance; dance is communication.

Translation Dance.note:
I was just in Mexico. And one evening there, I had the fascinating
experience of of listening to some Mexican and Columbian folks talking
—in Spanish—about the differences between Colombian
Spanish and Mexican Spanish.

My Spanish is pretty bad. I didn't know all the words. But I was able
to follow this conversation.  Partially because a lot of it was literally
explanation, but also because... they were dancing around each other.

It didn't matter that I didn't know all the words, because they were
exploring the graph, revealing the connections, revealing the topography
of a cognitive landscape.

Shows Up in How We Talk.note:
The physicality of language shows up in other ways. It shows up in how
we talk. A *lot*.

We take *stances* on issues: yours might be on the left, or the right.

When we've said too much, we walk back.

When you walk back too often, you're flip-flopping, or dancing around
the issue.

We move towards ideas we want to embody and distance ourselves from
ideas we no longer like.

All Metaphors.note:
These are all metaphors, of course, but I'd argue that our readiness
to liken concepts to positions suggests that they are processed
very similarly in our brains. The newly-evolved faculty of language
relying on ancient circuits evolved to do the hardest thing in the world:
move around in it.

The Larynx.htmlFunc: (_, res) => ` `
The Larynx.note:
Language has deeply shaped our bodies. The human voice box is capable
of some pretty incredible feats, feats no other animal can quite
reproduce.

Some birds do a remarkably good facimile, but our primate cousins
don't. Tell me, Mr. Anderson, what good is recursive grammar when you
are unable to speak?

Gesture-first theory.note:
Michael Corballis and others have offered a solution: language did
not arise with speech. It arose with gesture. The first languages
were *sign* languages.

And this seems at least viable. We know of primates who can use sign
language. And once sign language is established, there are some good
adaptive reasons to transition to the spoken word. For one thing, speech
allows us to communicate over greater distance, when line of sight isn't
available, and when our hands are otherwise occupied—possibly with spears.

Of course, the machinery has to change little. We already use acoustic
information to build up a physical model of our surroundings. Tweaking
*how* that information is integrated seems almost within the plasticity of
our individual brains, to say nothing of the capacity for evolution to
change the structure of those brains.

Other theories.note:
There are other gradualist theories of the origin of language. Some folks
say language began as grunts intended to synchronize manual labor. Heave, ho.

Others—and I do love this theory—say that it began as baby talk: coos
and babble between mothers and children that slowly gained semantics.

Some literally say that language started as dance.

I doubt we'll ever be able to truly disentangle which of these theories
actually happened. Not that it matters so much. All these theories speak
to truths about language. They all sound plausible enough; we can see
each theory reflected in our experience of language today.

markdown: But language has evolved.

data.note: But language has evolved.

Tree.note:
We have now a perfusion of languages spread across the globe.

This beautiful tree, drawn by Mina Sundberg, just shows the old world
languages, those from Europe and Asia.

Most of them are descended from Proto-Indo-European, a language spoken
by people in the Ural steppes four to six thousand years ago.

There are, of course, many more.

There were earlier languages we have since forgotten, and it was these
earlier langauges which shaped our bodies, giving us vocal chords, and
shaped our minds, giving us stories. Narrative, that thread from which
we weave our cognitive worlds.

That's power. And it flows both ways. Language, this thing we made without
even fully realizing we were making it, has shaped us just as much as we've
shaped it.

Living Things.note:
Where does language exist? A particular language, the English language,
where is it?

Well, it's in me. It's a program, running in my mind. But not just mine.
It's in yours, too. And hers, and his.

It's a distributed program running on a biological strata. A concept
given tenancy on an infrastructure of many minds.

Each one of us holds a shard. Language is organized into shards, just
as we are organized into cells.

Replicate.note:
The shards replicate. They are taught and learned.

The shards adapt. The language we learn is not exactly the language
we were taught. The language of youngs, rather famously, is not
quite the language of olds.

Biological systems, too, are made of self-replicating components, and
because of this they adapt and grow and come to homeostasis.

They are governed by laws of statistical mechanics which guide them
into shapes that can effectively obtain energy and convert it into heat.

And language too, evolves in this way. Everything we build evolves.

Everything comes alive.

Everything we make joins an ecosystem that includes us.

That shapes us.

That becomes a part of us.

Magic.note:
What we are doing, then—what all of us in this room are doing—

is Magic.

The oldest magic. Living things creating new living things. Living
things reshaping themselves.

This is a great power.

And with great power comes... well, you know the rest.

data.note:
We have now a perfusion of languages spread across the globe.

This beautiful tree, drawn by Mina Sundberg, just shows the old world
languages, those from Europe and Asia.

Most of them are descended from Proto-Indo-European, a language spoken
by people in the Ural steppes four to six thousand years ago.

There are, of course, many more.

There were earlier languages we have since forgotten, and it was these
earlier langauges which shaped our bodies, giving us vocal chords, and
shaped our minds, giving us stories. Narrative, that thread from which
we weave our cognitive worlds.

That's power. And it flows both ways. Language, this thing we made without
even fully realizing we were making it, has shaped us just as much as we've
shaped it.

markdown:
Where does language exist? A particular language, the English language,
where is it?

Well, it's in me. It's a program, running in my mind. But not just mine.
It's in yours, too. And hers, and his.

It's a distributed program running on a biological strata. A concept
given tenancy on an infrastructure of many minds.

Each one of us holds a shard. Language is organized into shards, just
as we are organized into cells.

Well, it's in me. It's a program, running in my mind. But not just mine.
It's in yours, too. And hers, and his.

It's a distributed program running on a biological strata. A concept
given tenancy on an infrastructure of many minds.

Each one of us holds a shard. Language is organized into shards, just
as we are organized into cells.

Replicate.note:
The shards replicate. They are taught and learned.

The shards adapt. The language we learn is not exactly the language
we were taught. The language of youngs, rather famously, is not
quite the language of olds.

Biological systems, too, are made of self-replicating components, and
because of this they adapt and grow and come to homeostasis.

They are governed by laws of statistical mechanics which guide them
into shapes that can effectively obtain energy and convert it into heat.

And language too, evolves in this way. Everything we build evolves.

Everything comes alive.

Everything we make joins an ecosystem that includes us.

That shapes us.

That becomes a part of us.

Magic.note:
What we are doing, then—what all of us in this room are doing—

is Magic.

The oldest magic. Living things creating new living things. Living
things reshaping themselves.

This is a great power.

And with great power comes... well, you know the rest.

experience them.

A warm beach.html: A warm beach on a sunny day.
A warm beach.note:
You see these words, and you go somewhere nice. You don't have to do
anything. In fact, you can't do anything.

Crackling campfire.html: A crackling campfire on an ice cold night.

As coders.note:
As creators and coders, I think we develop
an intuitive grasp of this. We develop physicalized inner
worlds that represent the abstract things we work with every day.

I see this? The triangle pops into my head.

Visceral.note:
And this... this taps something visceral. 

The feeling of a tiny creature crawling in your skin.

A compromise of bodily integrity.

I'm referring, of course, to Katie Hopkins. Whose words are designed
to *get into you*.

Trump.html:
“They don’t care about crime and want illegal immigrants,
no matter how bad they may be, to pour into and infest our Country.”
<cite>Donald Trump</cite>
Trump.note:
You can't help but envision them, and in envisioning
them, you can't help but form an association, and that association is
a spell, a power being enacted on your mind.

Jair.html:
“The only mistake of the dictatorship was torturing and not killing.”
<cite>Jair Bolsonaro</cite>
Jair.note:
This is, effectively, a security hole in our brains.

A security hole that is, currently, being exploited with alarming
efficency.

Hitler.html:
“Whenever Aryans have mingled their blood with that of an inferior
race the result has been the downfall of the people who were
the standard-bearers of a higher culture.”
<cite>Adolf Hitler</cite>
Hitler.note:
The exploits are not themselves new. But we are giving them powerful
new vectors, as we open more and more avenues for communication.

That's the downside of a connected world.
